<h1>The DIVERSE Toolkit -- using  MS Windows 2000/XP</h1>

<hr width=90%>

<h2>Binary Releases</h2>

<ol>

<li>
<b>Get the files</b> from one of the files dtk_win32-*.zip in
<a href="http://diversetoolkit.sourceforge.net/prereleases/binary/">prereleases/binary/</a> or <a
href="http://diversetoolkit.sourceforge.net/releases/binary/">releases/binary/</a>.


<li>
<b>Install it</b> by unzipping the source.  There is a nice free (as
in free beer) archive utility at <a
href="http://www.ultimatezip.com/">http://www.ultimatezip.com/</a>.

<li>
<b>Set PATH and DTK_ROOT environment variables</b>

<br>
To use the Micro$oft binary files (dtk_win32-*.zip) you may want
to set your PATH environment variable to include the directory where
you put the bin\ directory and the directory where you put the lib\
directory so that the DTK DLL may be found by running DTK programs.

Also set the environment variable DTK_ROOT to the directory where you
unzipped the files, so that DTK programs that load DTK DSOs (DLL
files) can find the DTK DSOs that are in sub-directories of DTK_ROOT.
This directoy should contain sub-directories bin, lib, include, and
a few more.

</ol>

<p>

To set Micro$oft environment variables on Windows 2000, and XP use the
menu:
<pre>
       <font color=#088008>Start</font>-><font color=#088008>Settings</font>-><font color=#088008>Control Panel</font>-><font color=#088008>System</font>-><font color=#088008>Advanced</font>-><font color=#088008>Environment Variables</font>.</pre>

</ol>

<hr width=90%>

<h2>Building from source</h2>


<ol>

<li>
<b>Get the source files</b> a file dtk-*.tar.gz from
<a href="http://diversetoolkit.sourceforge.net/prereleases/source/">prereleases/source/</a> or
<a href="http://diversetoolkit.sourceforge.net/releases/source/">releases/source/</a>.

<li>
<b>Untar the source</b>.  There is a nice free (as in free beer)
archive utility at <a
href="http://www.ultimatezip.com/">http://www.ultimatezip.com/</a>.

<li>
<b>Set environment variables:</b>
<ul>
<li>
<b>FLTK_LIB_DIR</b> to the directory where the FLTK library files
              are in,
<li>
<b>FLTK_INC_DIR</b>  to the directory where the FLTK include files
              are in,
<li>
<b>DIVERSE_ROOT</b>  to a directory that you would like DTK to
              put the DLLs, executables, and include files.
              There will be a bin, include and lib
                  subdirectory built in this directory.
</ul>

<li>
<b>Run Visual C++</b><br>

Open the file MSWindoz/VisualCPP/dtk.dsw using the Micro Soft Visual C++ program.

<li>
<b>Build the project dtk project</b><br>

In the MS visual C++ program build the dtk project.  This will put the
dtk DLL, binary executables, documents, and include files in
sub-directories of the DIVERSE_ROOT directory, that is gotten from the
environment variable DIVERSE_ROOT.

<li>
<b>Set PATH and DTK_ROOT environment variables</b>

<br>

To use the Micro$oft binary files (dtk_win32-*.zip) you may want
to set your PATH environment variable to include the directory where
you put the bin\ directory and the directory where you put the lib\
directory so that the DTK DLL may be found by running DTK programs.

Also set the environment variable DTK_ROOT to the same as DIVERSE_ROOT
so that DTK programs that load DTK DSOs (DLL files) can find the DTK
DSOs that are in sub-directories of DIVERSE_ROOT.
This directoy should contain sub-directories bin, lib, include, and
a few more.

</ol>

<p>

To set Micro$oft environment variables on Windows 2000, and XP use the
menu:
<pre>
       <font color=#088008>Start</font>-><font color=#088008>Settings</font>-><font color=#088008>Control Panel</font>-><font color=#088008>System</font>-><font color=#088008>Advanced</font>-><font color=#088008>Environment Variables</font>.</pre>


